"Acute Liver Injury and Acute Liver Failure"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_gi_s32_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"91afce",
"children":[
"In acute liver ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"injury"
]
},
", a sudden increase in serum ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"aspartate aminotransferase",
"children":[
"AST"
]
},
" and ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"alanine aminotransferase",
"children":[
"ALT"
]
},
" levels occurs."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"6138bf",
"children":[
"Acute liver ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"failure"
]
},
" refers to acute liver injury complicated by encephalopathy and coagulopathy in patients without previous cirrhosis."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d88f51",
"children":[
"The most common identifiable causes of acute liver injury are acetaminophen hepatotoxicity, idiosyncratic drug reactions, and ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"hepatitis B virus",
"children":[
"HBV"
]
},
" infection. Other causes include acute ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"hepatitis A virus",
"children":[
"HAV"
]
},
" infection, hepatic ischemia, herpes infection, mushroom poisoning, and Wilson disease. See also Liver Disease Associated with Pregnancy."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"34ac5f",
"children":[
"Drug-induced liver injury is most commonly caused by acetaminophen, antibiotics (particularly amoxicillin-clavulanate), and antiepileptic medications (phenytoin and valproate)."
]
},
{
